1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,080
We love them as people, they bring in all sorts of

2
00:00:20,080 --> 00:00:47,080
natural light, they're wonderful to have around, but from a physical security perspective they have some important implications.

3
00:00:47,080 --> 00:00:55,080
What we particularly need to focus on is what is the material that the window is made from, and there's a number of different things that windows can be made from.

4
00:00:55,080 --> 00:00:58,080
Let's start with the cheapest option, plate glass.

5
00:00:58,080 --> 00:01:02,080
Plate glass windows are simple plate glass windows, they're cheap glass.

6
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:10,080
The defining characteristic of plate glass is that when it breaks, it breaks into big scary shards, not very safe for people, you can get impaled.

7
00:01:10,080 --> 00:01:14,080
So plate glass is the cheapest option, but definitely not the safest.

8
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:18,080
If you want a safer type of window material, that is tempered glass.

9
00:01:18,080 --> 00:01:26,080
What happens when tempered glass breaks, it breaks into nice little small pebbles, and so you might get little nicks or cuts, but you're not going to get impaled.

10
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:29,080
So tempered glass, much safer for people.

11
00:01:29,080 --> 00:01:31,080
Wired glass.

12
00:01:31,080 --> 00:01:42,080
Wired glass is glass that has metal wires embedded in it, and I don't know if I just went to like a super sketchy elementary school, but all the windows in the doors in my elementary school had wired glass in them.

13
00:01:42,080 --> 00:01:54,080
The advantage of wired glass is that if the glass breaks, it gets held together by the metal wires, and you still have a barrier there from someone reaching in and undoing the door and on, for instance, because they're still the metal wires that are there.

14
00:01:55,080 --> 00:02:03,080
Laminated glass, as the name implies, the laminated glass is a lamination layers of different materials said which together.

15
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:08,080
Most commonly you'll have a layer of glass, a layer of plastic, and then another layer of glass.

16
00:02:08,080 --> 00:02:12,080
A really good example of this is windshields and cars.

17
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:20,080
Oftentimes when you get a rock chip on a car, and if it's in a nicer car, if you go to the outside of the windshield, you'll feel this big rock chip on the window.

18
00:02:20,080 --> 00:02:25,080
But if you go inside the vehicle and you feel in that same spot, there's nothing there.

19
00:02:25,080 --> 00:02:28,080
And that's because a lot of car windshields are actually laminated glass.

20
00:02:28,080 --> 00:02:33,080
There's a layer of glass, a layer of plastic, and then another layer of glass on the inside.

21
00:02:33,080 --> 00:02:36,080
It makes for a much stronger window.

22
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:39,080
The next type of material is polycarbonate.

23
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:44,080
And as the name implies, polycarbons, it's actually made out of plastics.

24
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:47,080
Now you may have heard of this concept of bullet proof glass.

25
00:02:47,080 --> 00:02:49,080
There is actually no such thing as bullet proof glass.

26
00:02:49,080 --> 00:02:51,080
There is bullet resistant glass.

27
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:56,080
And typically most bullet resistant glass is made out of polycarbons.

28
00:02:56,080 --> 00:03:03,080
And so if you ever get a question asking what's the strongest type of glass, the answer is most definitely polycarbonate.

29
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:10,080
Now the final thing we should talk about here of the different types of glass is actually not a type of glass but a coating that we can put on the glass.

30
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:12,080
And they're called solar films.

31
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:15,080
And solar films, you'll notice this in downtown buildings all the time.

32
00:03:15,080 --> 00:03:18,080
All the buildings that are covered in glass, they're different colors.

33
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:20,080
Gold, silver, greens.

34
00:03:20,080 --> 00:03:23,080
That's actually different types of solar films that have been applied to the windows.

35
00:03:23,080 --> 00:03:29,080
And the primary reason that we do that is that heat from the sun is a major heating factor in buildings.

36
00:03:29,080 --> 00:03:33,080
And it causes, it would drive up the prices considerably of cooling the building.

37
00:03:33,080 --> 00:03:38,080
And so these solar films actually block UV light, the light that brings in a lot of the heat.

38
00:03:39,080 --> 00:03:46,080
And so from a physical security perspective, we really like solar films because they help reduce the heating load on the building.

39
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:50,080
And the other thing you can use solar films for is to make what are known as one-way mirrors.

40
00:03:50,080 --> 00:03:56,080
Having spent a lot of time on the wrong side of these, if you've been in an interrogation room, it'll look like a piece of glass from one side.

41
00:03:56,080 --> 00:03:59,080
But on the other side, there's a bunch of police looking at you.

42
00:03:59,080 --> 00:04:01,080
So those are solar films.

43
00:04:01,080 --> 00:04:07,080
The final piece that we'll talk about related to windows is, how do you detect if a window has been broken?

44
00:04:07,080 --> 00:04:10,080
And there's two major types of sensors that you can use to do this.

45
00:04:10,080 --> 00:04:16,080
There's what are known as shock sensors and glass brake sensors.

46
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:18,080
Glass brake sensors actually listen.

47
00:04:18,080 --> 00:04:20,080
They're essentially a microphone.

48
00:04:20,080 --> 00:04:23,080
And they listen for the specific sound that braking glass makes.

49
00:04:23,080 --> 00:04:27,080
So with a glass brake sensor, you can put like one sensor in a room.

50
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:30,080
And it'll monitor all the windows in a room.

51
00:04:30,080 --> 00:04:35,080
Shock sensors, on the other hand, are a little sensor that attaches to each individual window.

52
00:04:35,080 --> 00:04:41,080
And a shock sensor actually detects the shock, the vibration of a window being broken.

53
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:44,080
So here's one final really good question to think about.

54
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:51,080
Which of these sensors, shock sensors, or glass brake sensors, would be better in a noisy occupied room?

55
00:04:51,080 --> 00:04:54,080
And the answer is shock sensors.

56
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:55,080
Why?

57
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:59,080
Well, because shock sensors pick up the vibration of the actual individual window being broken.

58
00:04:59,080 --> 00:05:03,080
Versus glass brake sensors listen for the sound of a window braking.

59
00:05:03,080 --> 00:05:07,080
And in a noisy occupied room, they probably wouldn't be able to detect that sound.

60
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:10,080
So that's what you need to know about windows.

